full_text: Starbucks not going through traditional testing processes on new items the past two years is rather notable given that the chain introduced some big items. $SBUX

full_text: Starbucks no longer charging for non-dairy beverage modifiers would definitely cost the chain some revenue. Modifiers are a $1 billion business in the U.S. You got to believe a big chunk is simply people adding oat milk or almond milk to their drinks. $SBUX
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text: Starbucks has four access points - cafe, mobile order, drive-thru and delivery, plus three lines of business, hot drinks, cold drinks and food. "We have not had operating standards for time of service that we want for each of those elements. That's the problem ..." $SBUX
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text:
Starbucks earnings call summary: 

* Drinks in 4 minutes or less

* Condiment bars coming back
* Company slowing store growth
* Menu simplification is coming

$SBUX

full_text: One question I have is whether Starbucks used its traditional testing process (stage-gate) on Oleato, which was pushed by Howard Schultz. It probably didn't, and that's disturbing. \n\nThe olive oil thing is leaving the menu after less than a year. Better testing prevents that.
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text: Like it sure seems that Starbucks pushed through a new coffee platform, skipping normal testing processes, because its interim CEO went to Italy and decided it'd be a great idea to serve olive oil infused coffee, and quickly. Just a weird situation.
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text: Oleato wasn't terrible. The cold foam was pretty good. But it was always a giant question mark and customers needed to be introduced to the idea gradually. In any event, pretty easy menu elimination. $SBUX
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text: I'm on my way back home. You'll be happy to know that my ride back to the airport was free because I made @davidhenkes pay for it. I apparently cannot effectively utilize ride-sharing services well enough to be trusted with that responsibility.

full_text: Another thought on Starbucks earnings: They really should have hired Niccol (or another restaurant person) two years ago. That was a big mistake. \n\nThe company needed operations expertise. It instead went through a weird process that wasted two years and set the company back.

full_text: Howard Schultz is an absolute icon. But the company had problems two years ago that he foresaw. And then he hired a guy with zero experience in the restaurant industry. Just a weird situation. \n\nMuch of what we see now is just Brian Niccol the Restaurant Guy doing his thing.
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text: I'm all in favor of bringing in outsiders into the restaurant business. This was not one of those situations.\n\nOK end thread. I've done way over my thread quota for the day my apologies.

full_text: Couple of lessons here:\n\nChains like this were all the rage in the 80s and 90s. They all looked alike with similar menus. Gregarious servers, kitsch on the walls, substantial bar scene. By the mid-2000s we were noting a “sea of sameness.” The brands were struggling.
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text: There was Applebee’s, Chili’s, Ruby Tuesday’s, TGI Fridays, plus brands like O’Charley’s, Cheddars, etc. \n\nBut consumers don’t dine in at restaurants as much. When they do, they have a ton of choices. And these  brands are not at the top of the list. So they’ve been in decline.
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text: Ruby Tuesday has gone bk and is in Zombieland. O’Charley’s shut a bunch of restaurants. Some Applebee’s franchisees have had major issues. Now Fridays is a disaster.\n\nAnyway, whatever is left of the bar and grill sector is going to Chili’s.
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text:
More preliminary same-store sales:

Red Robin: 3.8%
Noodles: 0.8%
Shake Shack: 4.8%

Shake Shack also believes it can now get to 1,500 U.S. units. It previously said it could develop just 450 domestic locations. $SHAK $RRGB $NDLS
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text:
The 1,500 units is interesting. Very few chains ever get there (30 restaurant brands have that many locations). But that's a fundamentally different concept than the one that went public in 2015. 

Shake Shack at 450 units was an experience. Shake Shack at 1,500 needs more everyday consumers. That will change what it means to be Shake Shack. It could put pressure on the brand to lower some prices. Or it will put pressure on the company to do a lot more marketing. It won't be easy. 

In any event, such projections are not worth the paper they're printed on. But Rob Lynch has a different idea in mind for Shake Shack than did his predecessor. $SHAK
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text:
Interesting comments from Niccol, comparing mobile order v. drive-thru.

Drive-thru customers have a natural queue and a line. Meanwhile, there is no gate on mobile orders. They can come in all at once and sometimes even faster than customers can get in, so drinks are waiting. 

Starbucks is focused on fixing that sequencing to improve in-store experience. $SBUX
name: Jonathan Maze

full_text:

full_text:
Speaking of McDonald's, this is the 50th anniversary of the national introduction of the Egg McMuffin, which franchisee Herb Peterson created in 1971. 

McDonald's adding breakfast was a pretty big deal,  ushering in an era of fast-food and convenience-focused breakfast. About a quarter of the chain's sales come in the morning (or thereabouts). So that would be $13 billion nationwide, good enough to be the fifth largest chain in the U.S.

McDonald's will sell Egg McMuffins on the app on Sunday to celebrate. 

Oh, and bagel sandwiches are now available across the U.S. $MCD
